body:
This appears to be a bug in .NET Core.

When you run `dotnet xunit -internaldiagnostics`, the reported runtime graph is:

`
[DependencyContextAssemblyCache..ctor] Runtime graph: ['osx-x64','osx','osx.10.10','osx.10.10-x64','osx.10.11','osx.10.11-x64','osx.10.12','osx.10.12-x64','osx-corert','osx-x64-corert','osx.10.10-corert','osx.10.10-x64-corert','osx.10.11-corert','osx.10.11-x64-corert','osx.10.12-corert','osx.10.12-x64-corert']
DependencyContextAssemblyCache..ctor] Compatible runtimes: ['osx.10.13-x64','']
`

The dependency inside the `.deps.json` file shows `unix` as the runtime ID:

```json
"System.Data.SqlClient/4.4.0": {
  "dependencies": {
    "Microsoft.Win32.Registry": "4.4.0",
    "System.Security.Principal.Windows": "4.4.0",
    "System.Text.Encoding.CodePages": "4.4.0",
    "runtime.native.System.Data.SqlClient.sni": "4.4.0"
  },
  "runtime": {
    "lib/netstandard2.0/System.Data.SqlClient.dll": {}
  },
  "runtimeTargets": {
    "runtimes/unix/lib/netstandard2.0/System.Data.SqlClient.dll": {
      "rid": "unix",
      "assetType": "runtime"
    },
    "runtimes/win/lib/netstandard2.0/System.Data.SqlClient.dll": {
      "rid": "win",
      "assetType": "runtime"
    }
  }
}
```

This has the appearance of being a bug with .NET Core for failing to list `unix` as a compatible runtime for OS X/macOS. I verified this with macOS 10.13 and both .NET SDK 2.0.0 and 2.0.3.

Also, you forgot to upgrade the `dotnet-xunit` runner to `2.3.1`.
